.H 1 "Configuring DCE"
.P
This chapter describes how to use the \*Ldce_config\*O 
script to configure DCE software once that software has been installed.
.P
.nS note
Because of differences in DCE R1.1 platforms, the output in the sample 
procedures in this chapter may 
differ slightly from the output you see when you run the 
\*Ldce_config\*O script.
.nE
.P
.iX "code set registry" "creating"
.iX "csrc" "using"
This chapter also describes how to use the Code Set Registry
Compiler (\*Lcsrc\*O) to build a code set registry once DCE 
software has been configured. This step is only necessary
if you are configuring an "internationalized" DCE cell,
which is a cell that supports RPC applications that use
a wide variety of languages other than U.S. English.
.H 2 "Prerequisites" 
.P
.iX "configuration" "requirements"
Before you can configure DCE software, you must have installed 
it on each machine that you are configuring.  See Chapter 7
for instructions on installing the DCE software.
.P
You must run \*Ldce_config\*O on the machine you 
are configuring.  You cannot configure a machine 
remotely.  Additionally you must be logged into the local 
machine as root.
.P
.H 2 "Order of Configuration"  
.P
.iX "configuration" "order"
You must configure machines in a cell in the following order:
.AL
.LI
The master Security server 
.LI
The initial CDS server
.LI
A DTS server
.LI
A single DTS time provider
.LI
DCE client machines
.LI
DFS servers, Security and CDS replicas, GDA servers, 
Password Management servers, 
and 
additional time servers
.LE
.P
Note also that you must configure a CDS client 
on all Security server (master or replica) machines that are 
not running a CDS server.  You 
must also configure a Time client on all machines that are not running 
a Time server.  Be sure to configure the clients only after you 
have configured all servers.
.P
.H 2 "Split Server Configurations"
If you configure the master Security server and the 
CDS initial server on different machines, the cell 
is said to have a ``split server''
configuration. 
.iX "split server configuration"
If you choose a split server configuration,
you must take some extra steps in the initial cell configuration
phase.  This is because every DCE machine must be configured as a DCE client,
including
machines that are also configured as some kind of DCE server machine.
However, a DCE client configuration cannot succeed unless a CDS
server is available.
Therefore, the initial Security server machine cannot immediately
be configured as a DCE client, but must wait until a CDS server
machine is configured.
.P
This is not a problem when the
master Security server and CDS server are configured on one machine.
However, in a split server configuration, you must first configure
the Security server, then configure the CDS server on another machine, and
then come back to the Security server machine and configure it
as a DCE client or as an additional server.  The following steps 
detail these actions:
...\" 
.AL
.LI
Configure Machine 1 as a Security server machine.
.LI
Go to Machine 2 and configure it as a CDS server machine.
.LI
Go back to Machine 1 and configure it as a DCE client.
.LE
...\" 
.P
Note that if you configure the Security server machine as some
other kind of server machine (for example, as a DTS server), then it
will automatically be configured as a DCE client. So the following
scenario also works:
...\" 
.AL
.LI
Configure Machine 1 as a Security server machine.
The \*Ldce_config\*O script will prompt you with the clock synchronization
question discussed in the following subsection.  When it does this, answer
"\*Ln\*O."
.LI
Go to Machine 2 and configure it as a CDS server machine.
.LI
Go back to Machine 1 and configure it as a DTS server.
.LE
...\" 
.P
In this scenario, Step 3 causes Machine 1 to be configured as
a DCE client as well as a DTS server.
.P 
Consult the \*(Re for the current information on timing
and sequence constraints when bringing up split server cells.
.P
.H 2 "Clock Synchronization"
.P
.iX "configuration" "and clock synchronization"
All servers and clients 
being configured should have clocks that are at
least loosely synchronized.  Using the \*LSYNCH_CLOCKS\*O 
environment variable described in Chapter 10,
you can specify that the clocks will be synchronized automatically  
or that the user should be prompted to synchronize the clocks if they 
are out of synch by a specified amount.  For DFS configurations, 
the clocks should be synchronized automatically.
.P
While it is not required, it is recommended that you configure the
Security master server machine with a DTS server.  This will allow
Security clients to synchronize clocks with the Security server machine.
.H 2 "Security and CDS Database Size"
.P
Both the Security servers (master and replicas) and the CDS servers 
(initial and replicas) maintain databases.
The machine on which a Security server or a CDS server is 
configured must have sufficient disk space 
to accommodate these databases. 
The size required for the Security and CDS databases depends on the platform 
and the operating system.  Choose machines large enough to accommodate 
future growth.
.P
Use the following general requirements for the Security database:
.iX "Security database" "size"
.ML
.LI
For each principal:  1000 bytes of physical memory and 700 bytes 
of disk space.
.LI
For each account:  1700 bytes of physical memory and 300 bytes of 
disk space.
.LE
.P
The virtual size of the CDS databases increases substantially as 
new directories and objects are added. When entries are removed, 
the memory associated 
with them may be reused but is not deallocated. Although it can 
vary depending on the platform, each directory can use 
roughly 38.5 Kbytes of virtual space.  Process data size and paging space should 
also be considered. 
.iX "Cell Directory Service" "database size"  
.P
.H 2 "Accessing the DCE Configuration Menu" 
.P
.iX "DCE Configuration Menu"
All configuration functions are chosen from the DCE Configuration 
Menu.  To access the DCE Configuration Menu, at the DCE Main Menu, 
type \*L2\*O and press <RETURN>.
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script displays the DCE Configuration Menu. 
.oS 
DCE Configuration Menu (on \*Vhost_name\*C)

  1. Initial Cell Configuration
  2. Additional Server Configuration
  3. DCE Client
  4. DFS Client

 98. Return to previous menu
 99. Exit


  selection: 
.oE 
.P
From the DCE Configuration Menu, you can choose to configure any of the 
following items by typing the number associated 
with your selection at the \*Cselection\*O prompt:
.ML
.LI
Selection \*L1\*O, \*CInitial Cell Configuration\*O, lets you 
configure the master Security server, the initial CDS server,
and DTS servers. 
.LI
Selection \*L2\*O, \*CAdditional Server Configuration\*O, lets you 
configure the following servers:
.ML
.LI
Replicas of the master Security server
.LI
Replicas of the  initial CDS server
.LI
DTS servers
.LI
DFS System Control Machine
.LI
DFS Private File server
.LI
DFS File server
.LI
DFS Fileset Location Database server
.LI
GDA server
.LI
Password Management Server
.LE
.LI
Selection \*L3\*O, \*CDCE Client\*O, lets you configure 
DCE client machines for all components except DFS.
.LI
Selection \*L4\*O, \*CDFS Client\*O, lets you configure 
DFS client machines.
.LE
.P
The remainder of this subsection takes you through the steps to perform each 
type of configuration available from the DCE Configuration Menu.  Note that in 
the sample output, the \*LDCE_DISPLAY_THRESHOLD\*O environment variable
is set to the default, \*LSUMMARY\*O, therefore \*Ldce_config\*O 
displays only Error, Warning, and Summary messages.  
.P
See Chapter 10 for more information about controlling message logging. 
.P
.H 3 "The Initial Privileged User"
.P
When you configure the master Security server, 
you  
create an account for the initial privileged user of the registry database, 
login to that account, and are authenticated as the 
privileged user.  If you exit from the \*Ldce_config\*O script, 
re-invoke it, and choose \*CConfigure\*O from the main menu, you 
will be prompted to log in as this privileged user.  
Additionally, at other points in the configuration process, 
you may be prompted to reauthenticate as the 
privileged user. 
.H 3 "Specifying the Removal of Previous Configurations"
.P
When you configure your cell initially, by selecting items from the Initial Cell Configuration menu, 
or when you configure DCE clients or DFS clients, you may receive the following prompt:
.oS
Do you wish to first remove all remnants of
previous DCE configurations for all components (y/n)?
You should do so if you plan on re-configuring
all existing DCE components now. 
.oE
This prompt appears once in each \*Ldce_config\*O session.  This means that 
once you answer it, it will not appear again unless you exit \*Ldce_config\*O and 
then restart \*Ldce_config\*O.  
The prompt 
asks whether or not you want to remove the
previous DCE configurations.  
.P
To answer the prompt, you have two choices:
.ML
.LI
Type \*Ln\*O and press <RETURN> if any of the following are true:
.ML
.LI
This the first time you have configured DCE on the machine  
or you removed the previous configuration with the \*LREMOVE\*O option
.LI
If you are reconfiguring only some of the components
.LE
.LI
Type \*Ly\*O and press <RETURN> if you are reconfiguring all 
components.  
.P
If you enter \*Ly\*O, \*Ldce_config\*O stops all DCE daemons and deletes 
any data files associated with the daemons.  It displays messages telling you 
what it is doing while it does it. 
.LE 
.P
.H 2 "Performing Initial Cell Configuration"
.P
This section describes the tasks to configure the master Security server, 
the initial CDS server, and DTS time servers and time providers.  
These servers are the basic servers required for any cell.  
You must configure the master Security server and the initial 
CDS server before you can configure client machines, any 
DFS servers, and Security and CDS replicas.  
See "Configuring Additional Servers" for information on configuring 
client machines, DFS servers, and Security and CDS replicas.
.P
In the subsections that follow, all procedures start at the 
Initial Cell Configuration menu. 
.H 3 "Accessing the Initial Cell Configuration menu"
.P
All initial cell configuration functions are accessed from 
the Initial Cell Configuration menu. 
.iX "Initial Cell Configuration menu" 
To access the Initial Cell Configuration menu, 
at the DCE Configuration Menu, type \*L1\*O and press 
<RETURN>.
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script displays the following message:
.oS 
S:****** Configuring initial cell...
.oE 
.P
and then the Initial Cell Configuration menu.
.P
.oS
Initial Cell Configuration ( on \*Vhost_name\*C )

  1. Initial Security Server
  2. Initial CDS Server
  3. Initial DTS Server

 98. Return to previous menu
 99. Exit

 selection:
.oE 
.P                                            
.nS note
You can enter more than one selection at a time from the DCE Configuration
Menu.  Just be sure to separate the selections by spaces.  
For example to configure the master Security server and the 
initial CDS server, you would enter \*L1 2\*O.  This function can be
especially useful if you have set the environment variables described
in Chapter 10.
.nE
.H 3 "Configuring the Master Security Server" 
.P
.iX "Security Server" "configuration of master"
You must configure the master Security server before any 
other machine in the cell.  As part of the master Security server 
configuration, \*Ldce_config\*O creates the cell's initial 
privileged user and the registry database, which will contain 
users and accounts.   
Once the master is in place, you can create Security 
server replicas on other machines.
.P
.ig
************************************
.H 4 "Results of the Master Security Server Configuration"
.P
When you configure the master security server, \*Ldce_config\*O does the following:
.AL
.LI
Creates the following files on the configured machine:
.ML
.LI
\*L/opt/dcelocal/dce_cf.db\*O\(emThe DCE configuration file, 
.iX "dce_cf.db"
.iX "configuration file" "dce_cf.db"
which contains the name of the machine being configured from 
which the host principal name is derived and the 
name of the machine's cell
.LI
\*L/krb5/krb.conf\*O\(emThe Kerberos configuration. 
.iX "krb_conf"
.iX "configuration file" "krb_conf" 
file, which contains the name of the machine being configured 
and the name of the machine's cell
.LE
.LI
Adds the following entry to \*L/etc/services\*O:
.iS
kerberos       88/udp		kdc
.iE
The registered Kerberos IP port is 88.
If an existing Kerberos port entry is found with a 
port number other than 88, \*Ldce_config\*O asks 
if it should the existing Kerberos port entry to 88.
Unless you have a reason to do otherwise, you should change it to 88.
.LI
Starts the  following daemons:
.LI
\*Ldced\*O, which allows the Security server to register its endpoint.
For clients, the Security validation Service of \*Ldced\*O
periodically refreshes the ticket-granting ticket for the machine's principal.
The Security Validation Service  also validates the master Security server 
contacted during \*Ldce_login\*O command execution.
.LI
*\Lsecd\*O, the Security server
.LI
BELOW IS ONLY FOR CLIENTS
.P
.LE
.LI
Executes the \*Lsec_create_db\*O
command to create the registry database.
.LI
Assigns the cell administrator to the following groups:
.P
\*Lacct-admin\*O
.nL
\*Lsubsys/dce/sec-admin\*O
.nL
\*Lsubsys/dce/cds-admin\*O
.nL
\*Lsubsys/dce/dts-admin\*O
.nL
\*Lsubsys/dce/dfs-admin\*O
.nL
\*Lsubsys/dce/dskl-admin\*O
.LI
Creates the \*Lkeytab\*O entries for the
\*L/hosts/\*V<hostname>\*L/self\*O principal.
.LE
.H 4 "Configuring the Master Security Server"
**************************
..
.P
To configure the master Security server:
.AL
.LI
At the DCE Initial Cell Configuration menu, type \*L1\*O and press 
<RETURN>.
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script displays the following message:
.oS 
S:****** Configuring initial Security Server... 
.oE
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script prompts for the name of the cell in 
which the servers are being configured: 
.oS
Enter the name of your cell (without /.../): 
.oE 
.LI
Type the name of the cell and press <RETURN>.
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script displays the following message:  
.oS
S:****** Starting dced... 
.oE
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script displays the following prompt:
.oS
Enter keyseed for initial database master key:
.oE 
.LI
.iX "keyseed" "entering during configuration"
Type in the text string for the "keyseed," which is a temporary
DES key that is used to generate the registry's
master key (the key that the registry will use for account key
creation).  Press <RETURN>.
.P
The text you enter should not be easily guessed.  Note that it
is not displayed as you type it.
.P 
The \*Ldce_config\*O script prompts:
.oS 
Enter desired principal name for the Cell Administrator: (cell_admin)
.oE
.P
.iX "initial privileged registry user" "defining during configuration"
Type the name of the principal who will be the initial privileged user 
of the registry database (known as the "registry creator") and 
press <RETURN>.  You will use the account created by \*Ldce_config\*O for 
the principal you name here to log in to the DCE during subsequent component 
configurations.  
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script prompts: 
.oS
Enter desired password for the Cell Administrator:
.oE 
.LI
Type the password to be assigned to the initial privileged user account 
and press <RETURN>. Note that if you use the default password, \*L-dce-\*O you 
should change it to a more secure password after DCE configuration 
is complete. 
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script prompts for the password again to 
ensure it is correct:
.oS 
Re-enter desired password: 
.oE
.LI
Type the password again and press <RETURN>. 
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O prompts: 
.oS
S:****** The current highest UNIX ID for persons on this node is 30124.
        Enter the starting point to be used for UNIX ID's that
        are automatically generated by the Security Service
        when a principal is added using "rgy_edit": (30224)
.oE
.LI
.iX "principal UNIX IDs" "defining during configuration"
Type a UNIX ID number that will be used as the principal UNIX ID 
at which the 
Security server will start assigning automatically generated
principal UNIX IDs and press <RETURN>.  
The default is the value of the 
highest principal UNIX ID on the 
machine being configured, incremented by the value of the \*LUID_GAP\*O 
environment variable. Although 
the value you supply is not required to be  
higher than the machine's highest principal UNIX ID, if you supply a 
value that is less than or equal to 
the highest currently used principal UNIX ID, \*Ldce_config\*O 
issues a warning message and prompts you to reenter the UNIX ID.
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script prompts: 
.oS
S:****** The current highest UNIX ID for groups is 26.
        Enter the starting point to be used for UNIX ID's that
        are automatically generated by the Security Service
        when a group is added using "rgy_edit": (126)
.oE
.LI
.iX "group UNIX IDs" "defining during configuration"
Type a UNIX ID number that will be used as the group UNIX ID at which the 
Security server will start assigning automatically generated
group UNIX IDs and press <RETURN>.  
The default is the value of the 
highest group UNIX ID on the 
machine incremented by the value of the \*LUID_GAP\*O 
environment variable. Although the value you supply is not required to be 
higher than the machine's highest group UNIX ID, if you supply a 
value that is less than or equal to 
the highest currently used group UNIX ID, \*Ldce_config\*O 
issues a warning message and prompts you to reenter the UNIX ID.
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script starts the \*Lsecd\*O 
server and initializes the registry database.  As it does, 
it displays:
.oS
S:****** Starting secd...
S:****** Checking for active sec_client service...
S:****** Initializing the registry database... 
.oE
.P
When the master Security server configuration is complete, 
\*Ldce_config\*O returns the Initial Cell Configuration menu.
.LE
.P
.H 3 "Configuring the Initial CDS Server 
.P
.iX "Cell Directory Server server" "configuration initial"
The initial CDS server must in place for cell operation and before any 
of the cell's client machines are configured.  Other 
additional CDS servers can configured on client machines. 
.P
To configure the Initial CDS server:
.AL
.LI
At the Initial Cell Configuration menu, type \*L2\*O and press <RETURN>.
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script displays the following messages:
.oS 
S:****** Configuring initial CDS Server...
S:****** Checking for active sec_client service... 
.oE
.P
Then, the \*Ldce_config\*O script prompts:
.iX "multiple LANs" "defining during configuration"
.oS 
Create LAN profile so clients and servers can be divided into profile
groups for higher performance in a multi-LAN cell? (n)
.oE
.LI
At this point you have two choices:
.AL
.LI
Type \*Ly\*O to configure the machine with multiple local area 
network (LAN) capabilities and press <RETURN>.  You may want to use multiple 
LANs to organize how applications find objects in the namespace.  
When you respond \*Ly\*O, the \*Ldce_config\*O script creates a LAN profile
that allows the DTS clerks to synchronize with DTS servers on the local LAN.
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script prompts for the name of the LAN:
.oS
What is the name of the LAN?
.oE
.P
Type the name and press <RETURN>.  You can enter 
any arbitrary name.  The name is used by \*Ldce_config\*O 
to store cell profile information. 
.LI
Type \*Ln\*O to not configure the machine with multiple LAN 
capabilities and press <RETURN>.
.LE
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script completes the 
installation, starts the \*Lcdsadv\*O and \*Lcdsd\*O servers, 
creates the LAN profile (if necessary), and sets the appropriate ACLs.  
It displays the actions it takes as it takes them.
.P
When the configuration is complete, \*Ldce_config\*O returns the DCE Initial 
Cell Configuration Menu.
.LE 
.P
.H 3 "Configuring a DTS Server"
.P
.iX "Distributed Time Service servers" "configuring"
A DTS Clerk should be configured on each machine in a 
cell that consists of more than one machine.  
A minimum of three DTS servers is recommended for any cell containing  
three or more machines. 
.P
Note that you can use DTS commands to reconfigure DTS after the 
initial configuration is complete.  See the \*(Ac for more information.
.P
You can configure two types of DTS machines:
.ML
.LI
.iX "Distributed Time Service servers" "types"
.iX "DTS Clerks"
\*LClerks\*O\(emDTS clerks receive time values and adjust the
system clock accordingly.  Most DTS daemons are configured as clerks.
.LI
.iX "DTS Servers"
\*LServers\*O\(emDTS servers synchronize times in the cell in addition to 
performing DTS clerk tasks.  You can configure two types of servers: 
global servers for cells with multiple LANs and local servers for cells 
without multiple LANS.
.LE
.P
.iX DTS time providers"
You can optionally configure DTS servers with a time provider. 
A time provider obtains the time either from the system clock on the
machine on which the server is running a null time provider or from an
outside time source, such as radio, telephone, or satellite
(an NTP time provider).  The NTP
time provider interfaces with a host running the NTP time service, which
in turn should access a reliable time source.  
.P
You configure your cell's DTS servers first, then designate one 
of them as the location of a time provider, as well.  Section 8.7.4.3
provides instructions for configuring a null or NTP time provider on a
server machine.
.H 4 "Accessing the DTS Configuration Menu"
.P
DTS configuration is performed from the DTS Configuration Menu.  
To access this menu, at the Initial Cell Configuration menu, 
type \*L3\*O and press <RETURN>.
