.zA "def,13493,R1.2.2,Added dced_acl_patcher"
.H 2 "Modifying ACLs on the Master Security Server"
.P
.iX "\*Ldced_acl_patcher\*O"
.iX "Security Server" "changing ACLs"
.iX "Security Server" "remote administration"
.iX "ACL" "modifying on Security Server"
.iX "ACL" "remote administration"
.iX "ACL" "\*Ldced_acl_patcher\*O"
.iX "remote administration to Security Service"
Upon initial cell creation, security is strong and little remote access is
allowed \(em ACL settings on \*Ldced\*O objects are tight. 
To allow for more flexibility in remote administration,
you may want to modify the ACLs on certain \*Ldced\*O objects. 
As root, run the \*Ldced_acl_patcher\*O script on the master 
Security Server. This opens the ACL settings, while still preventing the
\*Lcell_admin\*O from having root access to all machines in the cell 
via \*Ldced\*O. 
.P
To modify the ACLs, follow these steps:
.AL
.LI
Log in as root on the master Security Server.
.LI
Kill \*Ldced\*O and patiently wait for it to terminate \(em termination can 
take up to several minutes.
.iS
\*C% \*Lkill -s TERM \*Vpid\*O
.iE
.LI
Restart \*Ldced\*O with the -r option:
.iS
\*C% \*Ldced -r\*O
.iE
Wait 30 seconds for \*Ldced\*O to start.
.LI
Run the \*Ldced_acl_patcher\*O script, which does not prompt you for information:
.iS
\*C% \*Ldced_acl_patcher\*O
.iE
.LE
.P
See Appendix A, for a comparison of 
the ACLs as they exist before and after running \*Ldced_acl_patcher\*O.
.zZ "def,13493,R1.2.2,Added dced_acl_patcher"
.P
.H 2 "Configuring Additional Servers"
.P
Using the \*Ldce_config\*O script, you can configure the following additional 
servers:
.P
.ML
.LI
Additional DTS servers
.LI
DFS servers
.LI
GDA servers
.LI
Security server replicas
.LI
CDS server replicas
.LI
Password Management server
.LE
.P
Before you configure additional servers ensure that:
.ML
.LI
The cell's master Security server and initial CDS server have been 
configured and started.
.LI
The machine on which you are configuring additional servers has been 
configured as a DCE client.
.LI
You are able to login as the initial privileged user of the 
Security database.
.LE
.P
.H 3 "Accessing the Additional Server Configuration menu"
.P
All procedures to configure additional servers start at the 
Additional Server Configuration menu.  To access this menu, 
at the DCE Configuration Menu, type \*L2\*O and press 
<RETURN>.
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script displays the following messages:
.oS
S:****** Configuring additional server...
S:****** Please wait for user authentication and authorization... 
.oE
.P
and then the Additional Server Configuration menu.
.iX "Additional Server Configuration menu"
.oS
        Additional Server Configuration ( on \*Vhost_name\*O )


         1.  Additional CDS Server(s)
         2.  DTS
         3.  DFS System Control Machine
         4.  DFS Private File Server
         5.  DFS File Server
         6.  DFS Fileset Location Database Server
         7.  GDA Server
         8.  Replica Security Server
         9.  Auditing
         10. Password Management Server
         11. Unconfigure Password Management Server



        98. Return to previous menu
        99. Exit



        selection:
.oE
.P
Note that if you have not been authenticated as the initial privileged 
user of the registry database in the current \*Ldce_config\*O 
session, \*Ldce_config\*O prompts you for the privileged user's name and 
password before it displays the Additional Server Configuration menu.
.P  
The following subsections describe the steps to configure each type of 
additional server in order as they appear on the Additional Server
Configuration menu.
.P                           
.H 3 "Configuring Additional CDS Servers"
.P
.iX "clearinghouse" "configuring replicas"
When you configure additional CDS servers, you create replicas of the 
clearinghouse database created during the configuration of the initial 
CDS server.  Replicas are useful to ensure the availability of name
information when the machine on which the initial CDS server runs is
unavailable.  A CDS server replica must be created on a different machine
than the one on which the master CDS server resides. 
.P
To configure the additional CDS servers:
.iX "Cell Directory Service servers" "configuring additional"
.AL
.LI
At the Additional Server Configuration menu, type \*L1\*O and press <RETURN>.
.nS note
If you attempt to configure an additional CDS server on the node where the
master CDS server is located, the \*Ldce_config\*O script returns and error
message, and you must start again.
.nE
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script displays the following messages:
.oS
S:******  Configuring additional CDS server. 
S:******  Waiting for node self-identity to be established... 
.oE
.P 
Then the \*Ldce_config\*O script starts the CDS client daemon, and prompts:
.oS
What is the name for this clearinghouse? 
.oE
.LI
Type the name to be assigned to the CDS clearinghouse and press 
<RETURN>.  (The name assigned to the initial clearinghouse is 
in the form \*Vmachine_name\*L_ch\*O.  You may want to continue this 
convention in naming clearinghouse replicas.)
.nS note
Existing documentation and \*Ldcecp\*O task scripts assume that you will follow
this naming convention.
.nE
.P 
The \*Ldce_config\*O script displays the following messages:
.oS
S:******  Initializing the name space for additional CDS 
          Server... 
S:******  Setting ACLs for the CDS clearinghouse /.:/host_ch... 
.oE 
and then prompts:
.iX "directories" "specifying replication during configuration"
.oS
Should more directories be replicated? (n)
.oE
.LI
At this point, you have two choices:
.AL
.LI
Type \*Ly\*O to replicate other directories on the machine and press 
<RETURN>.
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script prompts for a list 
of the directories to replicated:
.oS
Enter a list of directories to be replicated, separated 
by spaces, and terminated by <RETURN>:
.oE
.P
Type in the list of directories separated by spaces.  
Press <RETURN> when the list is complete.
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script automatically replicates the root directory.  To 
have \*Ldce_config\*O replicate other directories, you must specify the full 
pathname (including the \*L/.:/\*O) of each additional directory you 
want to replicate.  Specifying the root directory of a tree structure does not 
cause the entire tree structure to be replicated.  
(Note that once the configuration is complete, you can use the CDS
control program (\*Lcdscp\*O) to replicate directories at any time.)
.LI
Type \*Ln\*O to 
not replicate directories and press <RETURN>.
.LE
.P
The \*Ldce_config\*O script completes the configuration and 
returns the Additional Server Configuration menu. 
.LI 
When the additional server configuration is complete, exit \*Ldce_config\*O  
and log in as the initial privileged user (created during 
the configuration of the master Security server), and 
skulk the root directory using the 
following command:
.oS
\*Lset directory /.: to skulk\*O 
.oE
This action propagates a copy of the changed root directory 
information to all the CDS servers.  Note that use of several 
CDS servers may expand the time required to complete 
the propagation.
.LE
.P
.H 4 "Possible Configuration Errors"
.P
.iX "Cell Directory Service server" "errors during configuration of"
An additional CDS server configuration may fail if the \*Lcdsd\*O
has been successfully launched, but its clearinghouse has not been 
properly created.  Such an event may produce error messages like 
the following:
.oS
ERROR:   Error during creation of clearinghouse /.:/\*Vnodename\*C_ch. 
           Message from cdscp: 
           Failure in routine: cp_create_clh; code = 282109010 
           Requested operation would result in lost connectivity to 
         root directory (dce / cds)

ERROR:   Error during creation of clearinghouse /.:/\*Vnodename\*C_ch. 
           Message from cdscp: 
           Failure in routine: cp_create_clh; code = 282108908 
         Unable to communicate with any CDS server (dce / cds)
.oE
.P
.H 4 "Handling Configuration Errors
If you receive either of these messages, the 
clearinghouse is in an intermediate state and cannot be used or deleted, 
although the rest of the cell namespace and other servers are unaffected.  
To recover:
.AL
.LI
Skulk the root directory
.LI
Use the \*Lcreate clearinghouse /.:/\*Vclearinghouse_name\*O command while you are logged 
in as the initial privileged user on the newly configured CDS server machine.  
This command manually completes 
the configuration of the new server and its clearinghouse. 
.LI
Finally, skulk 
the root directory again.
.LE
.P
In rare circumstances, you may see the following error, which you can 
ignore.
.oS
ERROR: cdscp error during "define cached server" command. 
       Message from cdscp: 
       Failure in routine: cp_define_cached_server; code = 282111142 
       Cached Server clearinghouse already exists (dce / cds)
.oE
.P
The error results from \*Ldce_config\*O trying to repeat 
an operation it has already performed.  
.P
.H 3 "Configuring Additional DTS Servers"
.P 
The steps to configure additional DTS servers (selection 2 from 
the Additional Server Configuration menu) are the same as the 
steps to configure the initial DTS servers.  See Section 8.7.4
for instructions.
.P
.H 3 "Configuring DFS Servers" 
.P
.iX "Distributed File System servers" "configuring"
You can configure the following types of DFS servers:
.iX "Distributed File System servers" "types"
.ML
.LI 
.iX "System Control machine"
A System Control machine, which distributes system configuration information 
that is shared by all DFS server machines in a cell.
.LI
.iX "Fileset Location Database machine"
A Fileset Location Database machine, which tracks and records the locations
of all filesets.  At least one is required in each cell.  You can run multiple 
Fileset Location Database servers for to help ensure the server's availability 
at all times.
.LI
.iX "File Server machine"
A File Server machine, which exports LFS and non-LFS data to the global
DFS namespace.
.LI
.iX "Private File Server machine"
A Private File Server, which also exports file system data to the 
global DFS namespace.  A private File Server machine is controlled by the
owner of the machine, not by the system administrator.  The purpose of a
private File Server machine is to allow individual users to export a small
number of filesets.  A Private File Server does not support replicated 
filesets.
.LE
.P
.nS note
.iX " Binary Distribution machine"
System Control machines can also be used as Binary Distribution machine.
.nE
Although you must configure at least one Fileset Location Database machine,  
all other DFS server machines are optional.  Note that if your are configuring 
a System Control machine, you should configure it first because you are 
prompted to enter its name during the Fileset Location Database machine 
configuration.  Otherwise, you should configure the Fileset Location Database machine 
first.
.P
.H 4 "Prerequisites"
.P
.iX "Distributed File System server" "configuration prerequisites" 
Before you begin DFS configuration, be sure that you have:
.ML
.LI
Made
the planning decisions described in 
...\" Chapters 52 and 56.
...\" Module 6, titled ``DFS Configuration Issues,'' ``Managing DFS
...\" Domains,'' and ``Making Filesets and Aggregates Available.''
the \*(Ad.
These decisions include the following:
.ML
.LI
Choosing the first DFS machine
.LI
Determining the cache size on DFS client machines
.LI
Defining DFS domains
.LI
Setting up your cell's DFS tree structure
.LI
Determining which file system to use for \*Lroot.dfs\*O
.LE
.LI
.iX "root.dfs fileset"
Created the file system for the \*Lroot.dfs\*O fileset.
This file system can be either a DCE LFS fileset or a non-LFS file
system (non-LFS fileset).  To use a non-LFS file system, 
create the file system manually by using
your operating system's file system commands.
To use a DCE LFS fileset, create a DCE LFS aggregate with the DFS
\*Lnewaggr\*O command.
.P
Before setting up the \*Lroot.dfs\*O fileset, refer to 
...\" Chapters 52 and 56; in particular, Section 52.3.1.
the \*(Ad.
.nS note
The \*Ldce_config\*O script configures the 
Fileset Location Database Server on the
machine that exports \*Lroot.dfs\*O.
.nE
.LI
.iX "Distributed File System" "kernel required for HP-UX"
On HP-UX machines, ensured that the kernel is installed on
the machine being configured. This kernel, which is available on 
the installation tree, is named \*Lhpux.dfs\*O.  To install it, 
first rename the existing kernel(named \*L/hpux\*O) and then copy 
\*Lhpux.dfs\*O to the \*L/\*O directory, naming it \*Lhpux\*O.
.P
For other platforms you should run the DFS  kernel that is built
during the build process.  
(For OSF/1 machines, the \*Lfsvmunix\*O
kernel includes support for both DFS and DCE LFS. The
\*Ldfsvmunix\*O kernel includes support only for DFS, but
requires less disk and memory resources.)
.LE
.P
.H 4 "Configuring a System Control Machine"
.iX "System Control machine" "configuring"
To configure a System Control machine, perform the following steps:
